'''Salvage therapy''', also known as '''rescue therapy''', is a form of treatment given after an ailment does not respond to standard treatment.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Definition of Salvage therapy
  | work = 
  | publisher = MedicineNet.com 
  | year = 2006
  | url = http://www.medterms.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=9380
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2006-10-26 }}
</ref> The most common diseases that require salvage therapy are [[HIV]] and various [[tumors]]. The word is not clearly defined; it is used both to mean a second attempt and a final attempt.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = HIV Therapy 2006
  | work = 
  | publisher = Flying Publisher
  | year = 2006
  | url = http://www.hivmedicine.com/textbook/haart/salvage.htm
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2006-10-26 }}
</ref> Salvage therapy drugs or drug combinations have, in general, much more severe side effects than the standard line of therapy.

==Uses==

===HIV===
[[Antiretroviral drug]]s (ARVs) are given to slow down the HIV reproduction, which in turn increases quality of life and survival.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Antiretroviral Therapy (ART)
  | work = 
  | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] 
  | year = 2006
  | url = http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/arv/en/#what
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2006-10-26 }}</ref>  If the patient's viral load starts to increase instead of staying very low, it almost always means the virus has developed a [[Resistance to antiviral drugs|resistance]] to the ARVs. As more and more mutations develop, it becomes harder to select an ARV that will contain it. Salvage therapy is the attempt to contain it, even though there are no common options.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = SALVAGE THERAPY
  | work = 
  | publisher = The AIDS InfoNet
  | year = 2006
  | url = http://www.aidsinfonet.org/factsheet_detail.php?fsnumber=408
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2006-10-26 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061005093623/http://aidsinfonet.org/factsheet_detail.php?fsnumber=408 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-10-05}}
</ref> One definition in HIV therapy speaks of salvage therapy when at least one regimen containing [[protease inhibitor (pharmacology)|protease inhibitors]] has failed in a patient.
.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = HIV Medicine 15th Edition 
  | work = 
  | publisher = Flying Publisher
  | year = 2007
